<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F320FFEEFF15FA91FE5E617F" blockId="25.[192,455,1320,1344]" box="[192,455,1320,1344]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F320FFEEFF15FA91FEDC617F" box="[192,325,1320,1344]" captionStart="Figures 36–41" captionStartId="36.[192,287,1849,1871]" captionTargetBox="[211,1437,397,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[192,1440,378,1734]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="Figures 36–41. Beltia, dorsal habitus. 36) Beltia tilarana, male. 37) Beltia tisingalita, female. 38) Beltia tsachila, female. 39) Beltia vacilona, female. 40) Beltia weyrauchi, male. 41) Beltia weyrauchi, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713513" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713513/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Figures 38</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F320FFEEFE84FA91FEE8617F" box="[337,369,1320,1344]" captionStart="Figures 57–59" captionStartId="39.[192,287,1847,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[192,1440,665,1395]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Figures 57–59. Beltia, male genitalia: a) lateral view of median lobe; b) endophallic apical sclerites; c) en-face view of median lobe. 57) Beltia tsachila. 58) Beltia vacilona. 59) Beltia weyrauchi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713519" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713519/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">57</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F320FFEEFEA8FA91FE04617F" box="[381,413,1320,1344]" captionStart="Figures 67–74" captionStartId="41.[192,287,1849,1871]" captionTargetBox="[239,1437,245,1800]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[232,1439,235,1821]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figures 67–74. Beltia, female genitalia: a) ovipositor, ventral view; b) spermatheca. 67) Beltia osa. 68) Beltia placidula. 69) Beltia sanchezae. 70) Beltia tilarana. 71) Beltia tisingalita. 72) Beltia tsachila. 73) Beltia vacilona. 74) Beltia weyrauchi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713523" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713523/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">72</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F320FFEEFE7FFA91FE5E617F" box="[426,455,1320,1344]" captionStart="Figures 78–79" captionStartId="43.[191,286,1850,1872]" captionTargetBox="[192,1441,412,1699]" captionTargetId="figure@43.[189,1443,412,1702]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Figures 78–79. Distribution maps for Beltia spp. 78) Northwestern South America: B. confusa (star), B. gorgona (inverted triangles), B. placidula (blue circles), B. rugosa (red circle), B. weyrauchi (square). 79) Ecuador: B. awapita (hexagon), B. ledesmae (squares), B. napoensis (triangles), B. talaga (circle), B. tsachila (star)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713527" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713527/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">79</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F320FFEEFF15FAE1FD0761ED" blockId="25.[192,1441,1368,1491]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F320FFEEFF15FAE1FDE9614E" bold="true" box="[192,624,1368,1393]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
Description of female 
<typeStatus id="557E8800F320FFEEFE25FAE0FDF3614E" box="[496,618,1369,1393]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
Body ovate, dorsally convex; length 
<quantity id="4D3D9B47F320FFEEFBE5FAE0FB16614F" box="[1072,1167,1369,1393]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.1" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" unit="mm" value="9.1">9.1 mm</quantity>
. Head, pronotum, and elytra dull metallic golden green, scutellum green with coppery margin; antennae with scape dark green, antennomeres 2–5 dark reddish brown, remaining antennomeres bluish black. Legs and underside glossy dark green, tarsi bluish black (
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F320FFEEFDEFFA03FD0861ED" box="[570,657,1466,1490]" captionStart="Figures 36–41" captionStartId="36.[192,287,1849,1871]" captionTargetBox="[211,1437,397,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[192,1440,378,1734]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="Figures 36–41. Beltia, dorsal habitus. 36) Beltia tilarana, male. 37) Beltia tisingalita, female. 38) Beltia tsachila, female. 39) Beltia vacilona, female. 40) Beltia weyrauchi, male. 41) Beltia weyrauchi, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713513" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713513/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F320FFEEFF15FA52FDA9625B" blockId="25.[192,1440,1515,1636]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F320FFEEFF15FA52FE89623C" bold="true" box="[192,272,1515,1539]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Head.</emphasis>
Clypeus and frons densely aciculate-punctate, punctures separated by distance slightly less than their diameters; surface between punctures alutaceous, punctures separated by distance subequal to their diameters; frontoclypeal suture distinct, vertex with a distinct median impressed line, antennal calli small and poorly defined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F320FFEEFF15F9C4FB016328" blockId="25.[192,1440,1661,1815]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F320FFEEFF15F9C4FEB562AA" bold="true" box="[192,300,1661,1685]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Thorax.</emphasis>
Prothorax distinctly wider than long, L/W = 0.64, widest close to base; disc regularly, strongly punctate, punctures separated by distance subequal to their diameters; surface between punctures with numerous punctulae. Prosternum densely punctate, with dense whitish setae, posterior margin of intercoxal process distinctly concave, width of intercoxal process 1.5× diameter of procoxa. Mesosternum convex on anterior face. Metasternum smooth, metepisternum finely alutaceous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F320FFEEFF15F896FC8663B7" blockId="25.[192,1440,1839,1928]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F320FFEEFF15F896FE876378" bold="true" box="[192,286,1839,1863]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Elytra.</emphasis>
Evenly punctate, punctures separated by distance slightly greater than their diameters, surface between punctures with small punctulae; width across humeri 1.23× width across pronotum. Basal calli moderately developed, postbasal depression deep.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F323FFEDFF15FF60FB3B652D" blockId="26.[192,1440,217,275]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFF15FF60FED064CE" bold="true" box="[192,329,217,241]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Sterna glossy, with numerous long setae, surface of segments V–VII alutaceous. Terga sclerotized, bluish green, alutaceous; a few small spicules laterally on tergum III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F323FFEDFF15FE9EFE2065FD" blockId="26.[192,1440,295,450]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFF15FE9EFED16500" bold="true" box="[192,328,295,319]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Genitalia.</emphasis>
Ovipositor (
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F323FFEDFE0EFE91FDA4657F" box="[475,573,296,320]" captionStart="Figures 67–74" captionStartId="41.[192,287,1849,1871]" captionTargetBox="[239,1437,245,1800]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[232,1439,235,1821]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figures 67–74. Beltia, female genitalia: a) ovipositor, ventral view; b) spermatheca. 67) Beltia osa. 68) Beltia placidula. 69) Beltia sanchezae. 70) Beltia tilarana. 71) Beltia tisingalita. 72) Beltia tsachila. 73) Beltia vacilona. 74) Beltia weyrauchi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713523" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713523/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Fig. 72a</figureCitation>
) elongate, narrow (L/W = 5.47); sternum VIII with long, strap-like basal apodeme, slightly expanded and less strongly sclerotized in apical fourth; segment IX covered with microspicules, hemisternites with elongate basal rods; baculum distinct, elongate; gonocoxae about as long as wide. Spermatheca (
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F323FFEDFDEAFE30FD3D659E" box="[575,676,393,417]" captionStart="Figures 67–74" captionStartId="41.[192,287,1849,1871]" captionTargetBox="[239,1437,245,1800]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[232,1439,235,1821]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figures 67–74. Beltia, female genitalia: a) ovipositor, ventral view; b) spermatheca. 67) Beltia osa. 68) Beltia placidula. 69) Beltia sanchezae. 70) Beltia tilarana. 71) Beltia tisingalita. 72) Beltia tsachila. 73) Beltia vacilona. 74) Beltia weyrauchi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713523" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713523/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Fig. 72b</figureCitation>
) with receptacle elongate, a sclerotized raised opening for the spermathecal gland.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F323FFEDFF15FE61FDA7662F" blockId="26.[192,1440,472,528]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFF15FE61FE1C65CF" bold="true" box="[192,389,472,496]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
Male 
<typeStatus id="557E8800F323FFEDFEDBFE61FEE665CF" box="[270,383,472,496]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">allotype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity id="4D3D9B47F323FFEDFE26FE61FDCC65D0" box="[499,597,472,496]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.2" pageId="26" pageNumber="25" unit="mm" value="9.2">9.2 mm</quantity>
, color of head, pronotum, elytra, underside, and legs as in female; antennae entirely bluish black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F323FFEDFF15FD9FFDDB6601" blockId="26.[192,578,550,574]" box="[192,578,550,574]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFF15FD9FFE896601" bold="true" box="[192,272,550,574]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Head.</emphasis>
Punctation as in female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F323FFEDFF15FDEDFC2866B2" blockId="26.[192,1440,596,653]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFF15FDEDFEB56653" bold="true" box="[192,300,596,620]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Thorax.</emphasis>
Pronotum with proportions and punctation as in female. Prosternum narrower than in female (subequal to diameter of procoxa). Metasternum as in female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F323FFEDFF15FD1BFE5F6685" blockId="26.[192,454,674,699]" box="[192,454,674,699]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFF15FD1BFE866685" bold="true" box="[192,287,674,698]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Elytra.</emphasis>
As in female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F323FFEDFF15FD69FA3966D7" blockId="26.[192,1440,720,744]" box="[192,1440,720,744]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFF15FD69FED066D7" bold="true" box="[192,329,720,744]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Sterna with numerous white setae except for a glabrous area along midline of sterna III–VII.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F323FFEDFF15FD47FB866768" blockId="26.[192,1440,766,855]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFF15FD47FED16729" bold="true" box="[192,328,766,790]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Genitalia.</emphasis>
Median lobe robust, curved at a right angle, a sinuate lamina on lateral margin along inside curvature (
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F323FFEDFE9EFCA6FE2B6709" box="[331,434,798,823]" captionStart="Figures 57–59" captionStartId="39.[192,287,1847,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[192,1440,665,1395]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Figures 57–59. Beltia, male genitalia: a) lateral view of median lobe; b) endophallic apical sclerites; c) en-face view of median lobe. 57) Beltia tsachila. 58) Beltia vacilona. 59) Beltia weyrauchi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713519" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713519/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Fig. 57a</figureCitation>
); apex of median lobe tapered to a slightly off-center sharp projection (
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F323FFEDFAF8FCA6FA0A6709" box="[1325,1427,798,823]" captionStart="Figures 57–59" captionStartId="39.[192,287,1847,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[192,1440,665,1395]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Figures 57–59. Beltia, male genitalia: a) lateral view of median lobe; b) endophallic apical sclerites; c) en-face view of median lobe. 57) Beltia tsachila. 58) Beltia vacilona. 59) Beltia weyrauchi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713519" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713519/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Fig. 57c</figureCitation>
). Apical sclerite small, twisted, and somewhat paddle-shaped (
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F323FFEDFC7EFC86FB8B6768" box="[939,1042,831,855]" captionStart="Figures 57–59" captionStartId="39.[192,287,1847,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[192,1440,665,1395]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Figures 57–59. Beltia, male genitalia: a) lateral view of median lobe; b) endophallic apical sclerites; c) en-face view of median lobe. 57) Beltia tsachila. 58) Beltia vacilona. 59) Beltia weyrauchi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713519" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713519/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Fig. 57b</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
