<subSubSection id="C2DF6529F323FFEDFF15FC65FDB2602B" pageId="26" pageNumber="25" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F323FFEDFF15FC65FDB2602B" blockId="26.[192,1440,988,1044]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFF15FC65FEC267CB" bold="true" box="[192,347,988,1012]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Etymology.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFEB5FC65FE5367CB" box="[352,458,988,1012]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Tsachila</emphasis>
, named for the indigenous Tsachila people of 
<collectingCountry id="F2D27632F323FFEDFC3CFC65FBCB67CB" box="[1001,1106,988,1012]" name="Ecuador" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, who still inhabit the region where this species was found.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C2DF6529F323FFEDFF15FB93FEFC60BC" pageId="26" pageNumber="25" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F323FFEDFF15FB93FEFC60BC" blockId="26.[192,1441,1066,1155]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFF15FB93FED6607D" bold="true" box="[192,335,1066,1090]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be recognized by its large size and relatively coarse punctation on both the pronotum and elytra. The laminae along the curve of the median lobe are unique among the 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F323FFEDFA82FBF3FA39605D" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1881" box="[1367,1440,1098,1122]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFA82FBF3FA39605D" box="[1367,1440,1098,1122]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Beltia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
so far known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C2DF6529F323FFEDFF15FB20FB89612C" pageId="26" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F323FFEDFF15FB20FB89612C" blockId="26.[192,1441,1177,1299]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F323FFEDFF15FB20FEDA608E" bold="true" box="[192,323,1177,1201]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Remarks.</emphasis>
The female was selected to be the 
<typeStatus id="557E8800F323FFEDFD33FB20FCD7608E" box="[742,846,1177,1201]" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">holotype</typeStatus>
because it is in a much better condition than the male. The male abdomen and genitalia were badly broken during the pinning process; the drawing of the aedeagus is a composite of the various fragments found after dissection. This species is known from one locality in the foothills of the western Andes in 
<collectingCountry id="F2D27632F323FFEDFCE0FB42FC02612C" box="[821,923,1275,1299]" name="Ecuador" pageId="26" pageNumber="25">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(
